About ten or eleven of the clock (for l do not observe one fixed hour), according as the weather recommends, l betake myself either to the terrace, or the covered portico, and there l meditate and dictate what remains upon the subject in which l am engaged. From thence l get into my chariot, where l employ myself as before, when l was walking or in my study3 and find this changing of the scene preserves and enlivens my attention. At my return home l repose myself a while; then I take a walk3 and aster that, read aloud and with emphasis some Greek or Latin oration, not so much for the sake of strengthening my elocution as my digestion3 though indeed the voice at the same time finds its account in this practice. Then l walk again, am anointed, take my exercises, and go into the bath. At supper, if l have only my wife, or a few· friends with me, some author is read to us; and after supper we are entertained either with music, or an interlude.
